"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "epithelial cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9113472104072571, "span": {"begin": 663, "end": 679}}, {"id": ["CL:0000803"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IEL", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7605667114257812, "span": {"begin": 732, "end": 735}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "gluten-specific T cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.8026278018951416, "span": {"begin": 794, "end": 817}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3458"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IFN-&gamma;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9936403632164001, "span": {"begin": 851, "end": 862}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7124"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TNF-&alpha;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9935492873191833, "span": {"begin": 864, "end": 875}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3558"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9894648790359497, "span": {"begin": 877, "end": 881}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3574"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-7", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9813763499259949, "span": {"begin": 883, "end": 887}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:59067"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-21", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9901963472366333, "span": {"begin": 893, "end": 898}}, {"id": ["CL:0000803"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IEL", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8504191637039185, "span": {"begin": 1018, "end": 1021}}, {"id": ["CL:0000803"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IEL", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8733063340187073, "span": {"begin": 1166, "end": 1169}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "gluten-specific T cell", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.7038002610206604, "span": {"begin": 1207, "end": 1229}}, {"id": ["CL:0000803"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IEL", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8529030084609985, "span": {"begin": 1313, "end": 1316}}, {"id": ["CL:0000066"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "epithelial cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5504454374313354, "span": {"begin": 1318, "end": 1333}}], "text": "While the disease underlying gluten-specific CD4+ T cell response is located in the lamina propria, celiac disease is also characterized by a pronounced increase in the presence of intraepithelial lymphocytes (IEL) that express Natural Killer-receptors in the epithelium (Setty et al., 2015). In addition, while IEL normally reside in the basal portion of the intestinal villi, in celiac disease they spread all over the epithelium, including the tip of the villi. These IEL are activated, express Natural Killer-receptors, and can mediate epithelial cell destruction, contributing to the flattening of the villi and loss of barrier function. IL-15 expression by epithelial cells is a key cytokine involved in the activation of the IEL (James et al., 2021). Also, the cytokines produced by the gluten-specific T cells in the lamina propria, including IFN-&gamma;, TNF-&alpha;, IL-2, IL-7, and IL-21 create a proinflammatory environment that is likely crucial for the increased presence and sustained activation of the IEL compartment as intestinal morphology normalizes upon the introduction of a gluten-free diet and is accompanied by a reduction of the numbers of IEL. Thus, a cascade where activation of gluten-specific T cell leads to a pro-inflammatory environment, which eventually results in activation of IEL, epithelial cell destruction and a loss of barrier function, and absorptive capacity in the upper intestine.     &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:11:21 +0000 2026"}